  1. Obtain the Data
    • Download the BIRDS 525 SPECIES dataset from Kaggle (CC0 license). You will need to create a free Kaggle account, and this will provide you free access to many such datasets, as well as code and even online notebooks.
    • Unpack the data. Notice that the data is organized into folders in a way similar to the Dogs vs Cats dataset that we worked with. This makes it easy to load with the same Keras function (ImageDataGenerator.flow_from_directory).
    • For this lab, we will work with the 3 classes with the highest number of images. Identify those classes, and use only these for the next steps. You can delete/discard the others.

In [4]:
data_folder = pathlib.Path('data')

d_train = data_folder / "train"
d_valid = data_folder / "valid"
d_test = data_folder / "test"

classes = []
class_dic = {}

for folder in os.listdir(d_train): # adding its name to the 'class_folders' list if a directory
    if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(d_train, folder)):
        classes.append(folder)

for name in classes:
    path = os.path.join(d_train, name)
    num_images = len(os.listdir(path))   #counting the number of file
    class_dic[name] = num_images

top3_classes = sorted(class_dic.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:3]
print(f"Three classes with the highest images:\n{top3_classes}")

Three classes with the highest images:
[('RUFOUS TREPE', 263), ('HOUSE FINCH', 248), ('D-ARNAUDS BARBET', 233)]
  1. Use data-augmentation to increase the number of training images. You are encouraged to try out various augmentation methods supported by Keras. The rule of thumb is that as long as an augmentation produces realistic images - it is probably a good idea to add it.(2 point)
In [5]:
augdataset =ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=30,
    width_shift_range=0.2,      
    zoom_range=0.2,        
    horizontal_flip=True,  
    fill_mode='nearest'    
)


training_generator = augdataset.flow_from_directory(
    d_train,
    target_size=(224, 224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical'
)

validating_generator = augdataset.flow_from_directory(
    d_valid,
    target_size=(224, 224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical'
)

testing_generator = augdataset.flow_from_directory(
    d_test,
    target_size=(224, 224),
    batch_size=32,
    class_mode='categorical',
    shuffle=False
)

In [8]:
#freezing the layers of VGG16 model
for layer in model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
    
x = model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
predictions = Dense(3, activation='softmax')(x)
model = Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=predictions)

model.compile(optimizer="Adam", loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
newmodel = model.fit(training_generator,epochs=10,validation_data=validating_generator)

pred= model.predict(validating_generator)
pred_cls = np.argmax(pred, axis=1) #predicted classes
real_classes = validating_generator.classes #actual classes
class_labels = list(validating_generator.class_indices.keys())

cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(real_classes, pred_cls)

print("Classfication report:\n", classification_report(real_classes, pred_cls, target_names=validating_generator.class_indices.keys()))
print("The classification matrix:\n", cf_matrix)

labels = keras.utils.to_categorical(real_classes, num_classes=3)  # Convert labels to binary format

for i in range(3):
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(labels[:, i], pred[:, i])
    auc_score = auc(recall, precision)
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f'Class {class_labels[i]} (area = {auc_score:.2f})')
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.title(f'Precision-Recall Curve for Class {class_labels[i]}')
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.show()
